segments.text: And you would be surprised how many newspapers and radio stations call me from all over the United States calling me a male chauvinist pig and what in the world was wrong.
And why in the world can you be that?
And ladies' organizations.
And it was a very trying experience.
And you'd go, so I'd go to a golf tournament, and my girl's going to play the first ball there, and there's somebody yelling over there.
And it was terrible.
Just five years of harassment, and it was bad.

uh all right five years i think it was five years before it started before it was over oh okay see they postponed it yes it may not have been i don't know at all i don't remember though i try to forget it i'm not going to ask the negative the positive uh who uh in the administration you mentioned colas who else deserves credit for being supportive of your effort to try to dr vanderbilt
I could tell you a little incident happened.
I won't tell you, but I'm not over this thing, but I'll tell you.
I'm telling you.
So I'm correct in understanding then that you believe that Dr. Frank Vandiver, then the president, deserves a lot of credit.
He deserves, in my, Dr. Vandiver and Dr. Colas, and of course the commandant, he's been for it for some time.
I believe his name was Burton at the time.
All right, then the first time the Aggie band goes on the field with women, how many were out there?
Maybe three or four, and you could not tell they were there.
That's what I heard from a number of people.
Everybody in the stands was trying to pick out the girls.
They couldn't do it.
They saw there was one little short one there that,
Stretching her legs out pretty good.

She was a flute player, but had her hair all day and she would the same thing and they still do it and now I think they have 35 right and they were They like the men wear slacks with same suit not skirt

the same thing, and I think they wear, when they go to corps dances and things, I think they wear the same thing as the women in the corps wear, their uniforms, but when they're marching on the field, they wear the same thing with their hair pinned up, and they're good.
Listen, women can play.
In my high school bands, we had some great bands, and about 50% of them were girls.
After that first year,

uh did everyone then seem to accept it it went after that they there was just some that didn't like it and we we had very few incidences the first year did you uh have to ever have to deal with any uh harassment or hazing well not anything real serious there were

you'd have to call one in there now this way it is and you go do it or else you're going to be in trouble and they'd go do it you know they were just that dedicated and and and uh i in my personal opinion i could never see as a parent if i were a parent sending a daughter in there it's a man's band

but you know then they moved them into the dorm you know with them and they they went in there one summer i was against that and i always will be i agree with you uh and they they went in there and they spent thirty five thousand dollars and fixed up a a restroom and they the first they moved them down on the end had their own little section but then that meant that all the boys on that section had to go somewhere to take a shower so you know i

Uh I just uh but I was not told and was not in on that so that's that's here and there but uh uh I just I felt like we did it smoothly and I felt like it was something that wasn't a matter of what we wanted it was a matter of what the the government was going to make you do then the Civil Liberties Union came down here and interviewed us and and and uh grilled us down and
And they asked why I object to it.
I said, you put young men and young women in the same building, doing the same things all the time, and things are going to happen that would not normally happen.
And I don't think that's right.
And they couldn't understand that either.
But I didn't care whether they understood it or not.
That's just the way it is.
Did any regents attempt to intervene and directly tell you what to do?
Not that I know of.
Good, good.
No, I didn't hear one thing from them other than that one request we talked about, which was kind of a stab in the night, I think.
All right, let's shift to some lighter moments.
Can you share some anecdotes about some of the tricks, some of the good bulls, some of the pranks that band members played on each other?
Yeah, they...
Somebody was always in the core, you know, they were always coming over there and driving on our football, on our practice field with the cars and making big tracks and things like that.
And they'd put sheep stuff and pig stuff and chicken stuff in there so it would smell bad for a long time and everything.
They would do things like that, but one of the best stories that I can remember is the last year I was there, we went to Arkansas.
And about 2 o'clock in the morning, the manager of the motel knocked on my door and said, Colonel, get up, get up.
You've got to come out here.
I said, well, what in the world does it matter?
It's 2 o'clock in the morning.
He said, that doesn't matter.
Come out here.
You've got to see this.
He said, there's a bunch of your seniors around there climbing up the trellis on the side of the motel.
They said they're going all the way to the top.
So I go out there, and I'm telling you, that's what it was.
It rose trellis, and they were halfway up.
And so I looked up there, and I said, what are you guys doing?
And they said, well, we're just having fun.
I said, you get down over there, and you go to your room, and we'll talk about it Monday.
Right now it's 2 o'clock in the morning.
The man is scared for a lot of insurance reasons and other reasons, and you get down and go to your room.
And they did.
I called them in Monday.
We had our talk.
So when we were going to the inaugural parade, I told them, I said, now I want to tell you guys one thing.
When we go up there, we're going to all be staying in the same motel for three nights.
If I hear of one lamp broken, one towel taken, one wash rag missing, or one disturbance call, I don't care who you are and you will be in Virginia
You will be on a bus at your own expense going home.
You will not perform in the parade, and you will not march with this band.
Do we understand that?
Yes, sir.
Okay.
So we go up there, and we go through the three days, march in the parade.
We're getting back on the bus to go to the airplanes, and they were in New York.
And this guy said, Colonel Haney.
I said, yes, can I see you in a minute?
He said, I'm Mr. So-and-so.
I'm the manager of this motel.
I said, oh, God.
So he said, you know, when I first got this call that we were keeping 315 members of the Fighting Texas Aggie Band, I was disturbed.
But he says, you know, they were here three days.
There was not one lamp broken, not one towel was taken, not one wash rag was missing, and I did not have one disturbance call.
And he said, that is a record.
And he said, any time you guys want to stay here, you're welcome.
So, now that's, to me, that's what it's all about.
Now, did ever any band members attempt to play any trick on you?
Not very.
Well, I'll tell you what.
Let me tell you one other story.

When I first came, the first year I was in in 73, I was up in the top floor up there is where I stay, and I was looking out and there was a big tree that grows all the trees all around the drill field.
And this one, I said, I didn't have my off button.
My on button, off button was on.
And so I said, you know, that dadgum tree is getting so big that I can't see half the band.
And I didn't think any more about it.
The next day I went out there and I said, there's something wrong.
That tree was gone.
They took it right down to the nub of the trunk.
And it was not a leaf in place.
Everything was gone.
Nobody mentioned it to me, nothing.
And I could see half the band.
So I said, oh my Lord, what have I done?
And so Mr. Ray, Eugene Ray, was the groundsman, and those trees were his children.
And it took him about two weeks to find it, to see it, notice it.
I guess he drove by or something and saw it.
So he didn't go to see John Coles, he went to see the president, Dr. Williams.
And so John called me a day or so later and said,
Joe, we got trouble.
I said, what's wrong?
He said, man, there's a $4,000 tree that those boys have cut down.
He said, do you know anything about it?
I said, John, all I can tell you is that the tree is gone.
And he said, well, I said, I couldn't see the band.
I told him my story.
He said, well, don't worry about it.
I'll take care of it.
That's the last I heard about the tree.
But now, they must have stayed up most of the night.
Mm-hmm.
And I told them one afternoon after band I said I can't back my car up, there's a car behind me and I've got to go home, it's 7 o'clock.
I said sir we'll take care of it and they've got a hundred of them over there and moved, picked that car up and put it on the sidewalk and left it.
I mean that's just the kind.
Not often did they.
Had one guy could imitate me real good, and one of the band dancers, he did that.
And I've got a picture of it in there.
I used to put my head up here or something, and he had my mannerisms down to better than I did.
And I thought that was so funny.
And we all got a big kick out of that.
Let's see, of all of the, I'll say tunes, to be as inclusive as possible, of all of the tunes, all the musical numbers that the band played, did you have a favorite?
Well, I just loved the Stars and Stripes.
Stars and Stripes Revival.
Yeah, and I loved, they really used to do it, of course I love the old men, they do that so well, and they do a great job on the National Emblem.

strategic air command and we had we had so many and of course that old battle hymn thing we did that was that was really something he stopped that a minute I mean go in this restroom and I'll be right back.
Before we leave the Aggie Band Association has just made a CD
of the two albums that Vern made and the four that I made.
It's two CDs and I want you to have the packet.
And they really are good.
And I think if you'll listen you can see how it never did really change except there's a little evolution there you can tell.
Now, in the halftime routine, always began with the war hymn and always ended with the spirit.
No, not at the halftime.

didn't play they don't play the spirit at the halftime they usually they usually end it with uh some kind of a march or something uh with the block t yeah with the block that's in the war here that's right yeah yeah all right uh then uh about in that halftime about how many other
were normally played every time during the halftime.
Were there any others?
You can usually, if you go with the war hymn, you can cut that off depending on how much.
But sometimes you'll just come out of the north end zone and then you'll go into something else that would require, change the mood a little bit.
And you can sometimes do three other tunes.
And you can do more than that if you just play a portion of them.
So you really need quite a variety, but see they have to memorize all those things, and they usually just want to play the ones, and they'll get lazy if you let them.
Now during the course of the football season, about how many different numbers will they perform in a year?
We used to pass out forty-five tunes.
Oh, that many.
I don't think they do that anymore.
They don't play quite that many anymore.
But we would play a number in the stands.
We did a lot at the pregame.
We played quite a bit.
And we would try to do some different tunes every week.
We might do during the process a year, do Noble Men twice maybe, and then some different finale every time.
But we would play most of those tunes during the football season.
Of course, some of them were basketball season.
And we played jazz when I was there in the basketball game some, and like the Saints go marching in and things like that.
But they've cut the band out now, and they have about forty I think, and there's no more national anthem.
There's no more spirit I don't think.
I don't know.
I haven't been.
And they have a dance team, I believe, with the rock tape.
That to me is not our tradition.
I'll tell you an interesting story on that one.
They changed that about the day I left because I wouldn't change it.
Let's see.
The title, Fightin' Texas Aggie Band, what does that fightin' mean?
I'm not real sure.
Because I've noticed that in all of the bands that we play, anywhere, Southwest Conference, anywhere, that our band is the best-mannered bunch of the whole deal.
We stay in there.
We mind our own business.
We very seldom ever have any trouble because we did not allow any trouble.
But I understand in days gone by, there have been some fights.

now I think one here one one let's see about two three years ago they got some they put the Aggie band and the Texas band on the field at the same time at Texas and they had some altercations and with with the Texas band and the football team and eight or ten of the seniors walked off they wouldn't get on there and uh they they asked I've had a number of them call me and I asked me I said

you need to do what the southwest conference rules say you can do and just tell them you got eight minutes i'm gonna be on there and off in eight minutes and you do whatever you want to the rest of the time and you won't have any trouble at all but uh because we always went right back to the stands and got back up in there so we we just didn't have any i don't ever recall having any really unpleasant experiences
at a game while I was here.
Because to me, I assumed that word, fighting, didn't mean physical encounters.
It meant striving, trying.
That's the way I interpret that, too.
Hardworking.
I interpret it that way.
I think like dedication and hard work and talent and
They're striving to do that.
But I think in years past they've had some altercations.
I've got only two or three questions left.
What have I not touched on?
Well, we've hit it around there pretty good, haven't we?
All right, then if you don't think of anything else, these questions.
Who are some people that you'd like to thank?
Express appreciation and record it.
Golly knows there's so many of them.
I just really wouldn't know where to start.
I think the first guy that was, of course, I'd like to thank Vern Adams first because Vern Adams was the reason I was there.
If Vern Adams had not wanted me
there I would not have been there and it's the same way for the guy they have out here now if I had not wanted him there and not brought him there he would not be here
Burn Adams is the reason that I was able to come to A&M.
And then John Coldis was very helpful to me when he first came and I first came.
And he was very nice to me and helped me a great deal.
And of course, all of the Aggie Band Association and those people, the former students,
There were a lot of people that I was in

the band went down here that are former students that still worked a lot with Aggie Band Association and that thing was kind of touch and go sometime because we didn't have the four or five that were doing everything and a guy named George Humble who I was in the band with was president for four years and he got the scholarships going and I mean the scholarships he got the foundation things going and established one in
Colonel Duns and Colonel Adams and in my name which and he started to raise the dues and establish some money and now they're they're they're working on the
the core foundation, I think, and they're putting all their money into that and getting more interest, I think, out of it.
I don't know how that's working.

But, you know, there's so many people that just day by day were so good to you, and certainly you want to say something about the coaches and the athletic department because primarily you're striving for them more than anyone because they're the ones that are
or making all of this possible.
If it were not for them, no football games, you couldn't have a 300-piece
Aggie band to play for six reviews, you know, that's something that you do extra.
And so I just feel like that all the coaches they've had, Coach Pillar and Coach Slocum and Coach Sherrill and Wally Groff and all those guys, they just were great to us.
And I just, General Simpson was very helpful in many respects.
When you first got here, Dr. Williams was here?
Dr. Williams was here, yes.
And he was very nice to me, always.
And then I'm just trying to think.
Howard Perry was my boss for a while.
He was a lot of help to me.
And mainly, the guys in the band were the ones that
golly knows if I had had a deal going with them it was not pleasant.
It would have been impossible to do all these things we had to do.
The last year I was there I had 45 performances I was responsible for.
And that's not quite as many as the singing cadets either.
Now you're talking about some people that go, singing cadets do.
But you know without their cooperation
And they call over there sometime on Wednesday.
Well, you've got to have them there.
You've got to have them so-and-so by Saturday.
But that's their weekend off.
Well, that's tough.
They've got to go.
And you call the COO and you say, look, I'm sorry, but that's what they say.
Sir, they'll be there.
All right, let's see.
Hypothetical question.
Let's make believe that you had an unlimited budget and unlimited staff.
How large would you think the A&M band ought to be in numbers?
If we had $10 million a year, I would be very selective and not march more than 303 people.
So you think that's... That is ideal with the company fronts and the manner in which you go into your block and the manner and the things.
It's large, but it does not limit your activities.
With 400 or 380 or whatever it is, you can't do much.

and and I had some so what we call a step one drill it takes three minutes to pick them up some way but this step one drill where they're turning every step you can pick them up the whole bunch in 24 steps and they save not only time and everything but

you can still do anything you need to do with 303 and that's that's what I would have and uh we've had had them smaller we've never tried one any larger but we've had them smaller 288 isn't bad that's what they marched that a couple times the first year I was here but then we lost a lot of them and uh

uh that's what i would do that's perfect for me okay next last question let's make believe somebody gave you a million dollar check and there's only one restriction on the check you got to pass it on to texas a m but you can decide what it would be used to support what would you make that check uh
I would be sure that we had first class horns to play all the time, and the music.
And we pretty well traveled okay, and I would put it in a trust and use it when we needed it, but I would not have to.
We had some horns that were so bad when I came here they wouldn't even play.
Had old E flat horns, E flat basses and stuff like that.
And John Colas helped me get some things.
But I had to go out and raise $25,000 myself one year to get bases, because they didn't have any money.
How much does a base horn cost around here?
Now it costs about $5,000 or $6,000.
Per horn?
Per horn.
It was about $3,000 then, $250.
But it's just, well, gosh, it's hardly gone up so there.
Of course, it's about $900 now.
Can you imagine?
All right, the last question then, as you look back on it, what has it meant to you and your life that you had to have this long association with Texas A&E?
Well, first of all,
I did not make the Aggie band.
If I have had any success and recognition, it's because of what they did for me.
Now, I think that I gave them some really nice things to do, but it has just meant so much to me to be associated with that bunch of dedicated people.
That was what made it so much fun, is because they were not only intelligent now, they were not only fine players,
But they had a wonderful attitude.
They were dedicated and that marvelous talent.
And they're just undying spirit.
There's just not another group in the world like that bunch.
And I think that's what got us through thick and thin.
And sometimes you get so busy and you're so worried about this and worried about that that you forget what in the world they're doing.
And I think the people at the university forget that.
They think they're on the payroll.
And I always tried to take up for them and fight for them.
And a lot of people probably thought I was disagreeable.
But if I didn't do it, who was going to do it?
You cannot make those guys, and it hurts their grades.
You can't tell me it doesn't hurt their grades.
It does.
They need to have time to study, and they need to have time to do the things that they want to do and have some time off.
And that's what I tried to do.
Sometimes it worked, and most of the time it didn't.
But that's all right, too.
I don't care.
I don't ever remember going somewhere with that bunch, and they didn't try to do their best.
And I don't remember many times that they didn't do their best.

Now you're going to have some problems because nothing a thousand miles away is like it is over the phone and you had some some it seemed like the stadiums in the last two years they were not on top of everything and they'd say well you get there so and so and this will be so and so and it was never there you had to go look it up and it was just a big hassle but that bunch I I'm not sure they're they're not uh they they were very disciplined then
And I didn't instill them.
No, I told them if we're going to leave at 6 a.m., we left at 6 a.m.
I said, sir, but there's eight seniors sacked out.
And I said, well, if they don't get there, we're going to have eight holes.
we went to Texas Tech and left eight of them one time and they were there waiting on us when we got there.
We didn't see them go by those buses either.
And also the next time they didn't oversleep.
Well and I've had I've had the uh the bus man tell me said man you know sometimes now we stick around 30-40 minutes waiting on somebody to come.
I said man we don't wait on anybody they're not there then

and getting up and leaving at 1 30 in the morning so you could have a 12 o'clock or one two hour game and then uh in the afternoon with tech or arkansas or lsu or something it's a hard deal but they made it easy that's the only way i survived this teaching business that long well let me thank you so much for this and i'll turn this machine off
